<br>
If your group think they do more damage with a Knight around, they're simply delusional.  It might be better for you and the group that you never got into that group.  I know plenty of uber casters that can maintain no net gain of mana without me trying very hard at all because they know when to nuke.  If a decked out max FT wizard can keep his mana constant with me doing nothing more than autoattack, then your pickup group casters can do the same, assuming they want to learn.  Get a good puller sometimes and see how little, if any, damage a Knight can actually squeeze if the mobs are coming at a constant pace.  Your casters cannot do more than their normal sustained DPS if they don't get a chance to med betwen pulls and it's fairly trivial to maintain aggro over casters at sustained DPS level.<br>
<br>
I'm also not sure where these secret areas people go LFG at, but when I join a decent pickup group in any zone that resembles remotely populated, we usually run out of mobs to kill.  All the DPS in the world isn't somehow going to make you XP faster when you run out of mobs to kill.  Yeah, there are the not so good pickup groups too, but such groups aren't going to suddenly become a mean DPS machine just because a Knight is there, either. <p><!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=468916">Phantron</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub14.ezboard.com/bthesteelwarrior.showUserPublicProfile?gid=ninaor@thesteelwarrior>Ninaor</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>knows that Warriors are superior</span><br>  Posts: 36<br> <font color=#FF0000>(3/18/03 3:30 am)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   more sweet info to add :)</span><hr size=1> Ok, I'll *TRY* to keep this as short as possible.  I have more info to add as requested by previous posters.<br>
<br>
I was asked by someone previously in this thread to come up with more than one situation (forest giant irmin's in PoS) where defensive allows the group to do something they normally cannot do.<br>
<br>
Well, today I spent a LOT of time in PoV at a different camp than my normal IC/OC.  I was at DG.  And I was without my wife (63 cleric) there to help out.  I was in a true pickup group of 2 wizards, a ranger, a cleric, and an enchanter.<br>
<br>
Basically the day went nearly flawless.  About 4 hours of constant exp'ing and I died 2 times - and I was the only one in the party that ever died.  Both deaths were related to the over zealous pulling of the ranger during what the group had agreed to as &quot;afk breaks&quot; for bio/food/whatever.<br>
<br>
I am now a level 64 Ogre War and I was at this camp today to try and gain as much exp as possible.  I was sitting at about 1360 AC and 5475 HP fully buffed.<br>
<br>
This was my first time at this camp, and my first time of course fighting the crawlers, arachnae, and golems out there in that part of PoV.  Any of you who have ever fought these mobs probably know that the crawlers are pretty predictable - they all max for 508 and they don't get the &quot;lucky streaks&quot; of hits and ripostes that the spiders sometimes do and the golems OFTEN do.  I however did not know this - and one of the times my cleric was caught off guard was also one of the times I died due to a string of red in my melee spam window along with a double proc of 375 DD per hit.<br>
<br>
Anyway, as I tanked at this camp I learned.  I learned that we would occasionally have to pull a golem whether we like it or not, and I adjusted.  I started using defensive on golem pulls and having the ranger immediately pull another before defensive wore off so I would be protected from those lovely &quot;damage spikes&quot;.<br>
<br>
So this situation would be another example of one where the warrior has an advantage.  However, I'm not sure if this could be avoided by stuns but I definitely can assume that if it is avoidable by stuns then the stuns would have to land 100% of the time or the pally would most certainly be dead.  I mean if a warrior can't withstand the damage spikes and he has the same AC plus better mitigation and more HP's than a knight class, then how could the knight possibly withstand the same onslaught ?<br>
<br>
Also, on the subject matter of taunt.  My taunts were hitting 80+% of the time.  And this is not a &quot;gimp&quot; situation either.  This was an enchanter that would tash within the first 2 swings of my axe (which I would immediately follow with a taunt) and then slow within the next 6 to 10 seconds (which I would also follow immediately by a taunt).  My taunts were amazing me.  I mean after reading all the stuff on these boards I assumed that at level 64 I certainly wouldn't get more than 6 out of every 10 taunts to hold.  But yet here I was getting like 9 out of 10 to take hold.<br>
<br>
I think Kunthaak is on to something with the timing idea - I mean that was basically what I was doing - timing my taunts to be as soon as I saw the message that the mob was tashed or slowed.  And it was working like a dream.<br>
<br>
Some people in this thread choose to argue with myself or with Kunthaak or with Graal.  I guess you feel like you have to because we seem to be &quot;against you&quot; in this sort of &quot;debate&quot;.  I don't feel like I am against anyone - I'm simply bringing IN-GAME experiences and specific situations to the table to show that some of the nay-sayer views expressed here are very isolated incidents and on the whole I don't see my non-uber warrior with a Windblade as being in any kind of problematic situation where agro is concerned.<br>
<br>
Now the reason I bring up today's group in particular is because of what happened about 2 hours into the group.  We lost our chanter and had to go with a 63 chanter - 2 levels lower than the 65.  Of course when we asked the 63 chanter to come to DG he had just gotten a shouted invite to OC about 2 seconds before I sent my ooc invite.  What is interesting is that he messaged me and asked who our tank was.  I told him it was me - the 64 ogre war.  He immediately asked if I could hold agro well.  I explained to him that no one in the group had died yet (left out the 2 deaths I had cause they were not agro related - but rather afk/RL related).<br>
<br>
He decided to come to our camp (no idea why) and he really tried his hardest to get some agro.  He's one of those chanters that uses his pet to add to DPS.  Needless to say he was fairly impressed with me... probly thought a warrior couldn't hold agro.  He was tashing within the first few swings, slowing as soon as the spell timer recovered, then boggling, and then DOT'ing the mob.  Now some times he took a hit, some times I hit taunt before the mob's weapon delay.  There were even times he would sit down right after casting slow or the DOT and the mob would stick to me.<br>
<br>
There were a few fights where his pet did not attack because, try as he might, my taunts were outdoing the tash/slow/DoT strategy he was using and he could not take a hit from the mob.  It almost became a game with us after a while because he relaxed and realized he was not going to die in this group.<br>
<br>
Of course on the times that taunt would fail I would simply hit my shield hotkey (which is /assist followed by /shield) and the caster would be safe.  Granted we had to be slightly more careful when I was in defensive for a golem pull.... but then again there was no need to slow as quickly because I simply asked the healer to hit me with an elixir before I engaged the mob.  Problem solved - even unslowed the golems couldn't do much to me in defensive with an elixir going.<br>
<br>
Ok so I posted another HUGE post again <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->   Sorry.....<br>
<br>
Hopefully I have illustrated yet another situation where a warrior can give a sense of security to an exp group on the edge through the strategic use of defensive and shield while also explaining the strategic timing of the taunt key as I used it in the field.  I agree with Graal and Kunthaak on many points (hope I spelled both their names right) and I think we should all listen to actual in-game experiences before we attempt to pick apart and criticise a game engine that may be far more well-balanced than one would like to believe.<br>
<br>
I'm just an average geared warrior with 2 AA's at level 64 that has never been turned down for a group that a pally got into nor have I ever had someone tell me the exp was going too slowly.<br>
<br>
~Ninaor<br>
<br>
p.s. Later on in the night I was helping 4 more guildies get flagged in trials.  There was another group there that is very similar to the groups I have been in all 10 times I have beaten trials between level 60 and 64.  That group failed all night long try after try.  My group entered trials 3 times, and succeeded 3 times.  The MT for the other group was a 62 Troll SK.  He kept dying during the fight with the executioner and the rogue just could not tank him <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :p --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/tongue.gif ALT=":p"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
The only time I ever died to the executioner was on a lucky string of hits he got back when I was level 60.<br>
<br>
Coincidence?  Or could it be that the warrior really is a better overall tank and these extreme situations just bring out that point?<br>
<br>
