I dont think it's a major equipment issue, i know people who tank/taunt fine without EB type wepons, it is harder but can be done.<br>
<br>
I will say that i am not uber, and here is my magelo to prove it: <!--EZCODE AUTOLINK START--><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=373940">www.magelo.com/eq_view_pr...num=373940</a><!--EZCODE AUTOLINK END--> It probably has some lacking AA i forgot to add - but with that setup i tank golems fine, i can heal through a slowed golem completely on my own but it burns mana, if a shaman takes a few hits on ping/pong i heal with group tap anyway so one or two taps fills them up. It is ok for a mob to ping/pong now and again - if it happens all the time something is causeing it so evaulate if you can/need/want to stop that happenning or is it more efficent to say sod it and carry on.<br>
<br>
A good warrior can let me do a lot more DPS - an bad warrior can drop me around 2000 damage through spells per standard Valor mob, if i snare its closer to 2500-3000 damage depending how long it lives, then throw in melee DPS lost because i had to turn off attack or backout.<br>
<br>
Any good group will pick a warrior to tank if they know they are not going to loose significant DPS - The fact is if i dont want to group with warriors i dont know because i loose to much DPS, then other classes must feel simular.. there are some class act warriors who taunt out there and do not have hate procing wepons, they taunt because they work with the group and learn to fit.<br>
<br>
Anyways, i dont mean to sound negative, but i love it when i have a fine warrior tanking so i can do DPS - but when i cant find those warriors i cring at haveing anyone else... and about the thing about warriors only getting a group unless it's a friend, guild or well known - thats the same for any class, a bad or exceptionaly good cleric, overnukeing wizard or wizard who is know for spotless evac timing, the monk that pulls good or the monk that trains you all... It's the same for every class not just warriors.<br>
<br>
Braellar<br>
 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#2F2F4F><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub14.ezboard.com/bthesteelwarrior.showUserPublicProfile?gid=graalthedorf>Graal the Dorf</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>is a Formidable Opponent</span><br>  Posts: 198<br> <font color=#FF0000>(3/18/03 8:51 am)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: more sweet info to add :)</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>So this situation would be another example of one where the warrior has an advantage. However, I'm not sure if this could be avoided by stuns but I definitely can assume that if it is avoidable by stuns then the stuns would have to land 100% of the time or the pally would most certainly be dead. I mean if a warrior can't withstand the damage spikes and he has the same AC plus better mitigation and more HP's than a knight class, then how could the knight possibly withstand the same onslaught ?<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Stuns do help, usually. Being able to stop an unslowed mob from swinging from 1-4 seconds is very, very nice early in the fight. I only have 1 stun that will actually stun 60+ mobs though and it has a long recast time and relatively high mana cost - I still love it though. It is fast casting (high fizzle rate, but nothing is perfect) and if I can channel it through it buys me a little more time. <br>
<br>
I don't really think warriors have better mitigation than a knight with the same AC. They will have slightly better avoidance from higher D/P/R caps, but it isn't anything really noticeable except through parses, I would imagine. The main difference is the hp differential between a warrior and a knight of the same level/gear more than anything else, IMHO. Other than disc defensive, which as Glatius rightly pointed out, isn't really something to rely on for each mob. That being said, it sure as hell is nice to have for the situations that need it. The same can be said for LoH and HT too, of course. LoH and HT generally won't allow a knight to tank something that would defensive would allow an equivalent level/geared warrior too tank.<br>
<br>
Knights can and do tank the golems in PoV just fine, it just requires a bit better gear than a warrior would need to tank at the same level with the same healing support, barring the constant use of defensive. <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Also, on the subject matter of taunt. My taunts were hitting 80+% of the time. And this is not a &quot;gimp&quot; situation either. This was an enchanter that would tash within the first 2 swings of my axe (which I would immediately follow with a taunt) and then slow within the next 6 to 10 seconds (which I would also follow immediately by a taunt). My taunts were amazing me. I mean after reading all the stuff on these boards I assumed that at level 64 I certainly wouldn't get more than 6 out of every 10 taunts to hold. But yet here I was getting like 9 out of 10 to take hold.<br>
<br>
I think Kunthaak is on to something with the timing idea - I mean that was basically what I was doing - timing my taunts to be as soon as I saw the message that the mob was tashed or slowed. And it was working like a dream.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
I'll be honest and say that I stopped giving the argument that warrior taunt is broken as much credence when I saw the overwhelming reply to the &quot;Are you a masher?&quot; poll. That poll, along with some in game experiences (including a 3 hour xp session that included the use of no stuns, just the taunt button) made me to come to the conclusion that some people are exaggerating the problem wildly, not realizing the benefits a warrior has over a knight, and/or simply do not understand how to use the taunt skill. <br>
<br>
Every time I've been grouped with a warrior in PoV it has been a matter of course that the warrior is the tank. It isn't even discussed. There is no comparison of level, AC, or hp. It's a warrior, he's the tank. Period. I personally prefer that, since it allows me to use my spells to produce actual benefits like crowd control and healing instead of having to use the majority of my mana maintaining aggro.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>And Graal, while your groups may never have tried the PoS giants, my groups have. And I die about half the time because the Clerics can't compensate for how hard the giants hit, even with slowed. I would never want to face one of those things for more than a few split seconds unslowed, I'm already dying fairly regularly with them slowed. Maybe it's just bad luck or bad Clerics, but it happens.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
The point I have been trying to make is that if it is borderline for a warrior to tank, it is undoable by an equal level/gear knight with the same healing support. If you were dying half the time, it likely would have been 75-90% of the time for me, at best. Most likely, an equal level/geared knight simply wouldn't be able to do it at all with the same healing support. And to be completely honest, while I think that sucks (for me), I also know that there is a valid reason for that. I just think you underestimate how important that advantage is.  <p><!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=14686">Graal MacBladefury</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--><br>
Crusader of Brell</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub14.ezboard.com/bthesteelwarrior.showUserPublicProfile?gid=glatius2>Glatius2</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>will kick your @$$</span><br>  Posts: 868<br> <font color=#FF0000>(3/18/03 9:27 am)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: more sweet info to add :)</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Most likely, an equal level/geared knight simply wouldn't be able to do it at all with the same healing support. And to be completely honest, while I think that sucks (for me), I also know that there is a valid reason for that. I just think you underestimate how important that advantage is.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Tanking something that is going to kill me about half the time is not a particularly valid experience group situation.  Yes, I can do it, if I'm willing to throw the dice and lose.  But that doesn't really move the experience bar much.  So other than saying we did it or to try and gather quest pieces, it sure isn't something I'd want to do regularly.  I'll grant you my chances of surviving are better than yours, but they aren't good enough to make it a particularly desireable activity. <p>The Man in Black: We are men of action, lies do not become us. <br>
